Sentence: Plenty of newcomers — with names like hakia and Snap — are trying to beat Google at its own game.
In Silicon Valley, the Race Is On to Trump Google

As Google continues to outmaneuver its main search rivals, Yahoo and Microsoft, plenty of newcomers – with names like Powerset, hakia, ChaCha and Snap – are trying to beat the company at its own game.
And Wikia, a company started by a founder of Wikipedia, plans to develop a search engine that, like the popular Web-based encyclopedia, would be built by a community of programmers and users.
In Silicon Valley, the Race Is On to Trump Google
The latest patent dispute pits Apple, Google and Napster against a company that closed five years ago.
Patent Lawsuit Names Leading Technology Firms
Google, in typical eccentric fashion, has created an automated way to search for well-rounded candidates.
Google Answer to Filling Jobs Is an Algorithm

Intertainer, a video-on-demand company, last week filed a broad lawsuit asserting that Apple, Google and Napster are infringing on a 2005 patent that covers the commercial distribution of audio and video over the Internet.
Apple, Google and Napster Named in Patent Lawsuit

In a move to expand beyond the search business in the world’s second-largest Internet market, Google has made an investment in Xunlei NetworkTechnology, a Chinese Internet video firm, the company said.
A Google spokesman said that the investment in Xunlei would be announced today in Beijing, but he declined to give details.
According to wire services, the China Daily reported that Google will team up with Ceyuan Ventures, a venture capital firm in Shangai, to buy a stake in Xunlei, which is in Shenzhen.
According to the reports, Xunlei’s Web site attracts more than 50 million visitors a day and more than 80 million users have downloaded its software.
The Xunlei deal would be Google’s second in as many days in China.
Google is also teaming with China Mobile, that country’s largest mobile telecommunications carrier, to deliver search services to cellphones.
China: Google Invests in Internet Firm

Google, which recently closed its $1.65 billion purchase of the video-sharing Web site YouTube, has bought a stake in China’s Xunlei Network Technology, which provides file-sharing and other services.

The move was widely seen as an attempt by Google, which dominates the Internet search market in the United States, to compete better with Baidu.com, which controlled nearly 57 percent of China’s search-engine market at the end of June, according to Analysis International, an information technology research company based in Beijing.
Google Buys Stake in Chinese Multimedia Site

As if YouTube  did not have enough trouble with its users posting clips that violate copyrights, the video-sharing site, newly acquired by Google, must now find a way to remove a video depicting a Merrill Lynch banker and a supermodel in what the Associated Press calls “intimate scenes.” A Brazilian judge this week ordered YouTube to filter out the video, which was the talk of Brazil when it first surfaced last fall.
Amorous Brazilian Banker Wins Round With YouTube
Apple, Caterpillar, Google, Kellogg and Toyota are among the smartest companies when it comes to what they reap for their research and development dollars.
Who Is Best at R&D?
Google struck a deal to invest about $5 million in one of the country’s fastest-growing Internet start-ups, Xunlei.com.
Google Makes Another Investment in the Internet in China
Yahoo’s Go for Mobile 2.0 will let users find information like news, stock quotes and sports scores more quickly on their cellphones.
Yahoo Introduces Mobile Service Software
More Internet-literate workers are forwarding their office e-mail to free Web-accessible personal accounts.
Firms Fret as Office E-Mail Jumps Security Walls
YouTube can help studios build tremendous buzz for films and TV shows, driving Hollywood to try to work with it instead of against it.
Hollywood Asks YouTube: Friend or Foe?
Google is in talks to acquire Adscape Media in a move to expand beyond its traditional Internet search advertising business and into video games, according to The Wall street Journal.
A deal for Adscape, a closely held San Francisco firm whose technology allows for the placement of ads over the Web in video games, could be reached as early as this week, the report said.
Google in Talks to Buy Internet Ad Firm, Report Says
The British Broadcasting Corporation said that it was in discussions with Google about putting some of the BBC’s programming on the online video site YouTube.
A BBC spokeswoman confirmed the talks but said a deal had not been signed.

YouTube, which was acquired by Google in October for $1.65 billion, has been approaching broadcasters and other owners of copyrighted material to arrange for the site to carry more authorized material.
Britain: BBC in Talks With YouTube
The World Economic Forum in Davos has yet to start and already reports are surfacing about the first deal to be announced there.

The Guardian wrote Monday that the British Broadcasting Company was in talks with Google to make programming available through a branded channel on YouTube, the video site the Internet giant bought last year for $1.65 billion.
Davos in the Papers: Google, Trade Talks, Dark Rooms

Regulators should hold off on ruling how the New York Stock Exchange charges for its market data until questions about its new status as a for-profit group are resolved, the Securities Industry and Financial Markets association, a Wall Street lobbying group, has asked.

The NYSE Group, which owns the exchange, is preparing to charge fees for access to ArcaBook, the real-time market data system the exchange picked up when it merged with Archipelago Holdings last year.
Among the offerings the market is planning is real-time share-price data to Web sites like Google and CNBC, in return for a flat fee.
Lobbyists Ask for Delay on N.Y.S.E.
Data Fees Ruling
As politicians and moguls stream into Davos, some of them arrive with a discreet black envelope in their luggage.
It contains an invitation to what has consistently been one of the conference’s hottest events: the party hosted by Web search giant Google.
Google’s High-Octane Mixer
Yahoo predicted only modest improvements for this year, suggesting that it would continue to struggle to keep up with Google.
Profit Down, Outlook Up at Yahoo

Yahoo closed the books on a tough year Tuesday, reporting that its sales rebounded in the fourth quarter from an especially sluggish third quarter and promising investors that it would soon turn on technology that it hoped would close the widening gap with Google.
Profit Down, Outlook Up at Yahoo
Having been a player in one of the most dramatic stories of the dot-com boom and bust, Joe Kraus seems happy to be safely ensconced at the Internet giant Google.

Mr. Kraus founded Excite, which went from a university-sponsored search engine to (as Excite@Home) one of the biggest names in the Internet business before its spectacular crash and burn at the turn of the latest century.
He went on to found JotSpot, a maker of collaboration software that Google acquired in October.
Net Pioneer Settles Into ‘Nerd Paradise’
Riding two of the Internet’s big success stories, Google and YouTube, venture capitalist Michael Moritz of Sequoia Capital took the No.
1 spot on Forbes’s latest Midas List, an annual ranking of the top 100 dealmakers in technology and the life sciences.
Spinning Google and YouTube Into Gold
The sight of Larry Page and Sergey Brin is enough to strike fear into a newspaper editor’s heart.

After all, the giant Internet company they founded, Google, has become a powerful force for democratizing the distribution of news, blogs and other forms of information, a trend that has left many in the industry bracing for the day when the print newspaper is dead.
Google Guys Aren’t Writing Off Old Media
There is no more coveted party than the Google Party in Davos.
The Password Is… Everywhere
A favored online tactic to mock the president — altering the Google search engine so the words “miserable failure” lead to President Bush’s home page — has been neutralized.
Google Halts ‘Miserable Failure’ Link to President Bush
President Bush set broad goals last week for the adoption of alternative energy.
Hoping to take on the role of filling in the details is an unlikely group: Silicon Valley’s technology investors.
These venture capitalists, backers of giants like Google and Genentech, have traditionally been free-market advocates, favoring ideas and innovation over government intervention.
Now they are heading to Washington on a crusade to influence energy policy because they have a big stake in the outcome.
Tech Barons Take on Energy Policy
Skeptics were drowned out by the marketing campaign for Microsoft’s operating system on the eve of its arrival.
First the Wait for Microsoft Vista; Now the Marketing Barrage
Google’s blockbuster growth continued, but investors were apparently hoping for even better fourth-quarter results.
Google Posts Sharp Rise in Sales and Profits
Google reported a sharp rise in both sales and profit, driven by blockbuster growth of its search-driven advertising business.
Ads Drive Sharp Surge in Earnings at Google

As pundits, voters and Washington insiders wonder whether former Vice President Al Gore will jump into the 2008 presidential race, The San Jose Mercury News discusses what it calls a “political problem” for Mr. Gore should he choose to run.

The newspaper writes that Mr. Gore has become “enmeshed, and enriched, in Silicon Valley through his association with a close-knit elite that includes Apple‘s founder and chief executive Steven P. Jobs, Google‘s chief executive, Eric Schmidt, and a venture capitalist, John Doerr, a Google director.”
Al Gore, the Silicon Valley Guy
The parent company of MTV and Comedy Central demanded that YouTube remove more than 100,000 clips of its programming.
Viacom Asks YouTube to Remove Clips
YouTube says it will comply with Viacom’s request that it remove more than 100,000 clips from the Web.
Viacom Tells YouTube: Hands Off
Project Panama is Yahoo’s effort to close the wide gap with Google in the race for search advertising dollars.
A Long-Delayed Ad System Has Yahoo Crossing Its Fingers

In a sign of the growing tension between old-line media and the new Internet behemoths, Viacom, the parent company of MTV and Comedy Central, demanded on Friday that YouTube, the video-sharing Web site owned by Google, remove more than 100,000 clips of its programming.
YouTube, Viacom and Some Unfriendly Dealmaking
The biggest windfalls went to YouTube’s three founders and its principal financial backer, Sequoia Capital.
YouTube’s Payoff: Hundreds of Millions for the Founders
The biggest windfalls went to YouTube’s three founders and its main financial backer, Sequoia Capital.
Numbers Out on How Rich the YouTube Deal Was
Everyone suspected that the investors, founders and early employees of YouTube made tidy sums when it was acquired by Google for $1.65 billion in stock late last year.
How Rich Was the YouTube Deal?
Now We Know
Xerox’s Palo Alto Research Center is licensing patents and technology to a start-up with the goal of building a search engine that could rival Google.
In a Search Refinement, a Chance to Rival Google

Palo Alto Research Center, the Xerox spin-off that is hoping to sustain itself by licensing technology and forming partnerships with outside companies, is announcing a deal Friday that underscores that strategy.

The New York Times reports that PARC, as it’s known, is licensing a broad portfolio of patents and technology to a well-financed start-up with an ambitious and potentially lucrative goal: to build a search engine that could some day rival Google.
In a Search Refinement, a Chance to Rival Google
There is growing speculation that Google is finding it harder than expected to muscle its way into the radio business.
Google Encounters Hurdles in Selling Radio Advertising
Give birth to a tech idea in Silicon Valley, and the chances of success soar.
When It Comes to Innovation, Geography Is Destiny
A case involving newspapers in Belgium could affect cases that publishers have brought against the search company in other countries.
Google Said to Violate Copyright Laws
The Red Herring is reporting that Google has made another acquisition, this time agreeing to buy Adscape Media, which provides advertising within video games, for $23 million.

The article seemed to question the move, however, suggesting that the purchase “gives Google little beyond a few potentially interesting patents,” and adding, “don’t expect the Internet giant to announce big in-game ad deals with publishers like Electronic Arts anytime soon.”
Google Said to Buy Videogame Advertising Startup
Content-recognition software could address a major entertainment industry concern— songs and videos being posted on the Web without permission.
New Weapon in Web War Over Piracy
Customers expect e-commerce Web sites to entertain, inform and make transactions a snap, but spicing up a site is worth the effort only if the results can be tracked.
Meet Kate, and Stick Around
Google will unveil communications and productivity software aimed at businesses that will be accessible over the Internet.
A Google Package Challenges Microsoft
Sony bought video-sharing Web site Grouper in August.
Google picked up YouTube, the king of video sites, in October.
Now comes a report that Microsoft has taken a look at Revver, yet another venture-backed video-sharing startup.

CNET News.com reports that executives from Microsoft toured Revver’s Los Angeles headquarters last month to determine whether that company’s service could enhance Soapbox, Microsoft’s own, newly launched service.
YouTube Rival Catches Microsoft’s Eye
Google is working with Dow Jones, Condé Nast, Sony BMG Music and other large content companies to syndicate their video content on other Web sites.
Google in Content Deal With Media Companies
Yahoo and Google are facing a challenge from a tiny adversary named Quigo Technologies over contextual text ads online.
An Ad Upstart Challenges Google
Talk that Microsoft might (or at least, should) acquire Yahoo has been going on for months.
On Monday, TheStreet.com’s Vishesh Kumar joined the chorus, writing that Google‘s continued encroachment on Microsoft’s territory might force the software giant’s hand.
Last week, Google, already the leader of the online search business, introduced an upgraded version of its applications suite, which directly targets Microsoft’s venerable Office product.
Google’s Moves Rekindle Microsoft-Yahoo Speculation
Unlike the last Internet boom, entrepreneurs in “Silicon Alley,” New York’s venture-capital community, is filled with older, more experienced entrepreneurs who focus more on long-term profits.
Internet heavyweights like Google have opened up ambitious new offices in the Big Apple.
But some things never change, according to The New York Sun’s Jay Akasie: Just like in the olden days, Silicon Alley still takes a distant second to the West Coast.
The (Potential) Rise of Silicon Alley 2.0
YouTube is set to announce a partnership with the BBC to create two entertainment channels and one news channel on YouTube.
Google Courts Small YouTube Deals, and Very Soon, a Larger One
Google is forming partnerships with hundreds of smaller media companies that see value in contributing to the site.
Google Courts Small YouTube Deals
Google disclosed in its 2006 annual report on Thursday that the U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission nearly a year ago had called into question how it accounted for income taxes.
In the annual filing, Google said it received a letter from the S.E.C.
in March 2006 on various issues and subsequently corresponded with the agency as recently as January 2007.
The tax dispute remains unresolved.
S.E.C.
Takes Issue With Google Tax Accounting
Just because Google spent $1.65 billion to acquire YouTube and is swimming in cash doesn’t mean that Google will seek a major deal again anytime soon, according to its chief executive.

Reuters said that at Morgan Stanley’s technology conference, Eric Schmidt, responding to a question by analyst Mary Meeker, said that it’s “highly unlikely” the company will change course on how it uses cash.
Google C.E.O.
Plays Down Deal Talk

Silicon Valley and its attendant news media were apparently left breathless by Google‘s “Radical Benefit for Humanity” fundraiser for the X Prize Foundation, the nonprofit group that already has awarded $10 million to designers of a private spacecraft.

The San Jose Mercury News raved that while Silicon valley fundraisers tend to be understated affairs, Google, ever the Silicon Valley iconoclast, has come up with its latest “innovation” for local philanthropists: “Glamour.”
Google Fundraiser Dazzles Silicon Valley
Trying to catch up with Google, Microsoft says it will change the way computer users search.
Searching for Michael Jordan?
Microsoft Wants a Better Way
The Microsoft executive who had led the effort to close the gap on Google is leaving the company.
Microsoft Executive Leaving
A tidbit in a regulatory filing late last week revealed that Google paid a whopping 100 times revenues for the video-sharing Web site YouTube.
Perhaps more remarkable than the sticker shock, however, was the rhetoric employed by Google’s chief executive, Eric Schmidt, to justify the deal.
“If you can build a sustainable eyeball business, you can always find clever ways to monetize it,” Mr. Schmidt told a group of investors Tuesday.
Was YouTube Worth It?
Chris Taylor is Business 2.0 magazine’s “Future Boy” blogger.
On Friday, he looked into the financial future of Internet startups and came up with a provocative thesis.
“Silicon Valley no longer needs Wall Street,” he declared.

Entrepreneurs and their venture-capitalist financiers have a better option than an initial public offering: being acquired by the Web’s “cash-rich superpowers.” Think Google, Yahoo, eBay and Amazon.com.
Can Silicon Valley Find the Exit?
A flurry of articles raising questions about Google‘s $1.65 billion acquisition of YouTube — a flurry that included an item on DealBook — totally misses the point.
That is the view of Henry Blodget, the author and former Internet analyst, who wrote about this recent negativity on his Internet Outsider blog.

Last week’s revelation that YouTube booked just $15 million in revenue last year, meaning that Google paid more than 100 times revenue for the video-sharing Web site, is basically “irrelevant,” Mr. Blodget wrote.
Defending Google’s YouTube Deal
The sheer scale of Google’s new shuttle program for its employees befits the company’s oversize ambitions.
Google’s Buses Help Its Workers Beat the Rush
The latest “intrusion” tactic, making good money in worthless options
Quadruple Your Money in Worthless Options
The parent company of MTV and Comedy Central is seeking $1 billion in damages for copyright infringement.
Viacom Sues Google Over YouTube Video Clips
Accusing Google and its YouTube site of “massive copyright infringement,” Viacom said it was seeking more than $1 billion in damages.
WhoseTube?
Viacom Sues Google Over Video Clips
Google said it would start to make search logs anonymous after 18 to 24 months.
Under current practices, the company keeps the logs indefinitely.
Google Changes Policy on Search Records
Ever since Google coughed up that $1.65 billion for YouTube, critics of the online video site have been predicting a landslide of copyright lawsuits.
While that landslide has yet to occur, the first boulder has fallen.

Viacom, the parent company of MTV, Nickelodeon and Comedy Central, filed a wide-ranging lawsuit against Google on Tuesday, accusing it of “massive copyright infringement.” Viacom said it was seeking more than $1 billion in damages and an injunction prohibiting Google and YouTube from committing further infringement.
Viacom Sues Google for $1 Billion
For months, pundits have been kicking around the (wildly speculative) idea of Microsoft buying Yahoo to take on Google, the giant of the Web search world.
John Battelle, the editor of SearchBlog, a blog on search technology, was among them.

But now Mr. Battelle, who also founded the online ad network Federated Media Publishing, thinks he has a better idea, though one he admits might sound “crazy”: a joint venture between the two companies to create a “search monetization” business.
Yet More Musings on a Microsoft-Yahoo Deal
Troubles in the mortgage market have put a spotlight on the arcane world of structured finance and the alphabet soup that includes CDO’s and CMBS’s.

These woes may also be creating additional opportunities for Wall Street workers who know about such complex things, according to MarketWatch’s David Weidner, who reports that “bankers and traders who have experience structuring collateralized debt obligations, or CDOs, are in high demand to feed departments handling securities backed by mortgages, assets, corporate debt and other loans.”
Fast Times for Wall Street’s Debt Whizzes
Google is taking steps to make anonymous the logs it keeps of all searches that people conduct.
Google Adds a Safeguard on Privacy for Searchers
Viacom, controlled by Sumner Redstone, is suing Google for $1 billion for copyright violations on its YouTube video service.
But CBS, also controlled by Sumner Redstone, is making licensing deals with Google for YouTube to use some of its content.
What gives?
On YouTube, Redstone Contains Multitudes
The problem for both Google and Viacom is that copyright law is filled with compromises and ambiguity.
Awaiting a Compromise on YouTube
Google purchased a video game advertising firm, Adscape, to expand into in-game advertising, Google said on Friday.
Financial details were not disclosed, but Red Herring last month reported the value of the expected deal at about $23 million.
Google Buys Adscape to Expand in Video Game Advertising

Microsoft‘s move to buy Tellme for about $800 million represents a boon for Benchmark Capital, as well as Kleiner Perkins Caufield and Byers, but no home run on the order of Google, says The Red Herring.
Benchmark Reaps Rewards of Microsoft’s Tellme Deal
The company said it would expand a test of a system that allows advertisers to pay only when an ad spurs a consumer to take an action.
Google Tests an Ad Idea: Pay Only for Results
The networks hope to offer high-quality versions of entire TV episodes on the Web on an advertising-supported basis.
NBC and News Corp. to Create YouTube Rival
Apple is finally being taken seriously not just by the true believers, but by just about everybody.
Apple Cult Becoming a Religion
A federal auction for a prized swath of spectrum has touched off an intense lobbying effort pitting cellular companies against new players interested in the mobile Internet.
Hot Spectrum Draws Cash, and Ideals
Much of the attention that venture capitalist John Doerr has drawn in recent months has focused on his environmental advocacy and investment in “green” technologies.

But, says The San Jose Mercury News, thanks to his investment in search engine powerhouse Google, Mr. Doerr in recent months has been quietly amassing the kind of green that Silicon Valley traditionally favors.
For Doerr, Google Makes Another Kind of Green
The auction for a prized swath of spectrum that could reshape the debate over who controls access to the networks that deliver digital content to consumers is about to go into high gear.

Among those maneuvering ahead of the auction for the spectrum, which could be used for voice services for cellular carriers, new frequencies for emergency responders, or a commercial high-speed broadband multimedia network, are the nation’s four largest cellular providers, rural and regional wireless carriers, cable and satellite television companies and a range of technology companies – including Google and Yahoo.
Hot Spectrum Draws Cash, and Ideals
Google’s efforts to sell radio and TV ads are mixed, suggesting that it is far from becoming a credible player in traditional media.
Google, Online Ad Giant, Looks at Radio and TV

Google‘s acquisition of video-sharing site YouTube was driven by a culture of “nerd logic,” which has slammed the company headfirst into the culture of New York’s Big Media, Clive Thompson wrote in New York magazine.
And, in a development that many had predicted, the deal has made Google the target of a major lawsuit from Viacom, which contends its copyrighted materials are being used without its permission.
Google, YouTube and ‘Nerd Logic’
SKS Microfinance, a fast-growing Indian company that provides financing for entrepeneurs, has received an $11.5 million injection with Sequoia Capital putting up most of the funds.

Sequoia, which has made such savvy previous investments as those in Google, Yahoo and YouTube, was joined in the round by Unitus Equity Fund, Vinod Khosla, Ravi Reddy, Odyssey Capital and prior investor Sidbi.
Sequoia Capital Backs Financier for Indian Entrepreneurs
Google plans to begin selling TV ads on the satellite programming channels distributed by EchoStar’s DISH Network.
Master of Search Seeks Mastery of the TV Dial

If Google and Microsoft are circling DoubleClick — a bidding feud that has been reported but never acknowledged by any of the parties — it may be based partly on a new initiative that the online advertising firm announced Wednesday.
DoubleClick May Entice Buyers With Ad Exchange
Eric E. Schmidt received a salary of $1 but his personal security cost shareholders $532,755, representing the bulk of his compensation.
Google’s Chief Gets $1 in Pay; His Security Costs $532,755
Google agreed to make it easier to remove offensive content posted on its Orkut social-networking site, heeding requests from prosecutors in Brazil.
Google will set up a page on Orkut where prosecutors will send requests to remove content, the Rio de Janeiro state prosecutor’s office said.

In Brazil, where Orkut is the most-used social networking site, prosecutors complained last year that the company was taking too long to comply with their demands to eliminate some material on the site.
Google, based in Mountain View, Calif., said it had added workers to review reports of offensive or illegal content, along with special tools for law enforcement to expedite reviews.
Brazil: Google Steps Up Oversight
Technorati is known for its software that searches and indexes thousands of blogs.
So the company is presumably quite aware of the buzz making the rounds on the Net, in which bloggers are speculating that Technorati is positioning itself for a sale.
Technorati has denied those rumors, but the denials may only be fanning the flames.

After Michael Arrington of TechCrunch (the blog that broke the news that Google might buy YouTube) wrote about the situation, he appended his post with this update quoting Technorati’s chief executive:
Blogs Blog About Blog Tracker’s Sale Prospects
National networks tested an online exchange designed by eBay to sell advertising time and decided that it went too far in removing humans from the ad sales process.
For Cable TV, No Interest in Selling Ads the eBay Way
AOL plans to introduce a service Monday to sell ads that will appear next to its search results, which are powered by Google’s Internet search engine.
AOL Moving to Increase Revenue It Gets From Search Ads
On YouTube, copyrighted video clips are far less popular compared with noncopyrighted material than previously thought, according to a new study.
YouTube’s Favorite Clips
Agence France-Presse, a global news agency based in Paris, said Friday that it had settled its lawsuit against Google Inc., the online search engine.
News Agency and Google End Dispute Over Use of Material
The market for initial public offerings of Internet startups has been weak in the past few years.
So for venture investors and Silicon Valley entrepreneurs seeking a way to cash out, a sale to Google, Yahoo and a handful of other Web giants has become the brass ring.
So what does Google, which has about $11 billion in cash and lots of high-priced stock to use as currency, look for in an acquisition target?
According to its chief dealmaker, Google likes ideas that are “really crazy.”
Google’s ‘Really Crazy’ Acquisition Strategy

Google reached an agreement Friday to acquire DoubleClick, the online advertising company, from two private equity firms for $3.1 billion in cash, the companies announced, an amount that was almost double the $1.65 billion in stock that Google paid for YouTube late last year.
Google Buys DoubleClick for $3.1 Billion
The sale gives Google access to DoubleClick’s software and its relationships with Web publishers and advertisers.
Google Buys DoubleClick for $3.1 Billion
Google agreed to its largest acquisition Friday, reaching a deal to purchase DoubleClick for almost double what it paid for YouTube last year.
Google Buys an Online Ad Firm for $3.1 Billion
Google will begin selling ads across all Clear Channel stations at the end of June, a partnership that represents a clear step forward.
Google Reaches Deal With Clear Channel to Sell Radio Ads
Microsoft contends that Google’s $3.1 billion deal to buy DoubleClick would hurt competition in the online advertising market.
Microsoft Urges Review of Google-DoubleClick Deal

Horton, First Data, Gannett, Google, Merck, Merrill Lynch, Nokia, Schering-Plough, Southwest Airlines, UnitedHealth Group and Wyeth (Thursday); Caterpillar, Honeywell, McDonald’s, SAP, Schlumberger and Xerox (Friday).
Looking Ahead
Yahoo announced a broad deal with publishers representing 264 newspapers to sell national advertising across their Web sites.
Yahoo Strikes Ad Deal With More Papers
Google‘s $3.1 billion acquisition of online advertising firm DoubleClick drove up shares of other Internet ad firms.
What was behind the rise?
Many investors were betting that Microsoft (which was reportedly also in the running for DoubleClick) and Yahoo would be driven to make deals of their own to keep up with Google.
DoubleCick Deal Puts Spotlight on Rivals
Who says venture capitalists have no sense of humor?
Well, if anyone was saying it, a recent venture by Sequoia Capital would put the kibosh on that notion.

The investment firm which has backed YouTube, Google, Yahoo, Oracle and Apple, among others, has partnered up up with funny man Will Ferrell and writer-director-producer Adam Mckay to launch FunnyOrDie.com, a comedy video site that began its beta release Thursday.
Sequoia Gets Its Kicks With Will Ferrell Web Site
Hellman & Friedman is having a busy week.

Just a few days ago, the San Francisco private equity firm agreed to sell portfolio company DoubleClick to Google for $3.1 billion, well above the $1.1 billion that Hellman and JMI Equity paid for the advertising firm just two years ago.
On Tuesday, Hellman & Friedman announced that it raised $8.4 billion for its latest private equity fund, giving it plenty of ammunition for more deals.
The new fund, which is the firm’s sixth, represents more than half of the $16 billion that Hellman & Friedman has raised since 1987.
Hellman & Friedman Raises $8.4 Billion Buyout Fund
Revenue and income were below expectations, suggesting that an overhaul of the search advertising system has yet to deliver.
Yahoo’s Earnings Are Down 11 Percent

All the entrepreneurs out there dreaming about being acquired by Google should take note: The two founders of Dodgeball, a mobile social-networking service Google bought in 2005, have quit, saying the company “wasn’t supporting Dodgeball the way we expected.”
A Deal With Google Ends With Some Bruised Feelings
What are those crazy venture capitalists in Silicon valley up to these days when they are not listening to pitches and signing deals?
Kiteboarding, apparently.

Bloomberg News takes a look at the sport, which has seduced the likes of Google co-founders Sergey Brin and Larry Page, as well as a slew of venture capitalists, private equity pros and investment bankers.
V.C.’s Grab Some Air
The company’s core search and advertising business continued to outpace that of Microsoft and Yahoo.
Profits Up 69% at Google, Exceeding Expectations
Google, Microsoft and Yahoo have trained their sights on cellphones as the next great battleground in the Internet search wars.
Big Money in Little Screens

Google‘s proposed $3.1 billion acquisition of online advertising service DoubleClick may alienate some of DoubleClick’s clients, who may fear that its new owners will end up competing with them, Forbes.com reported.
DoubleClick’s privacy issues could also resurface if it joined with Google, a privacy advocate said.
Google’s DoubleClick Deal Raises Competition Questions
Google’s $3.1 billion deal for the online advertising firm DoubleClick could put the company at odds with itself.
The Pangs of Two Becoming One
Four states have joined forces with Google to make information from their Web sites more directly accessible through Internet searches.
Google Seeks Clearer Path to State Data
Yahoo plans to acquire Right Media, a privately held company that runs an advertising marketplace, in part to bolster its position as a seller and broker of ads.
Yahoo to Buy Ad Company in Bid to Compete With Google
Weeks after Google spent $3.1 billion to buy the Internet advertising company DoubleClick, a rival search giant is reaching into its wallet in a bid to compete.

Yahoo has agreed to pay about $680 million to acquire the rest of Right Media, a privately held company that runs an advertising marketplace, in part to bolster its position as a seller and broker of ads outside its own sprawling network of Web sites, The New York Times reported.
Yahoo to Buy Online Ad Company Right Media
Responding to Viacom’s $1 billion copyright infringement suit, Google said that it would not back off, declaring that the law was on its side.
Google Calls Viacom Suit on YouTube Unfounded
Microsoft has emerged as a contender to buy the online advertising firm 24/7 Real Media in an effort to stay competitive with online rivals Google and Yahoo, The New York Post reported Tuesday.
Citing unnamed sources, the Post said that Microsoft is considering a bid of about $1 billion, a hefty premium over the $600 million value that analysts have given the firm.
Microsoft Is Said to Consider a Bid for 24/7
After reading this week's column, a reader named Anne Garcia sent an email to say that Ikea sells 9-inch plates for just 79 cents apiece.
The plates are part of the Motto line, and I have no idea how nice they are.
But a 9-inch diameter is impressively small for any dinner plate that isn't an antique.
I just did a Google search on "small dinner plates," and all of the sizes listed on the first page of results were more than 9 inches.
